, I got checked out around one on Wednesday. My mom picked us up and she told us we had to go back home for a little while because my dad needed to do something before we left. We came home and my sister was there. It was cool. We didn\'t leave until like 3 or later which made me mad because I could have stayed at school longer (it\'s not that I like work, I just had been home ALL frickin week and my house is so incredibly boring). We started driving down to Thomson, Georgia, and we all decided to go to sleep because I didn\'t have anything to do anyway. I called the backseat because it has the most room, but little did I know that my brother and sister in front of me were going to squish the POO out of me. I sat in the most uncomfortable position I have ever been in for 2 hours. I didn\'t know anybody could go without breathing for that long. We got to the hotel and my parents abandoned us! They just left us in the car and when I noticed that the stop light was geting a little long, I looked up and they were gone! I was like screw this I can barely breathe, I am NOT staying in this car. So I out on my hat and jumped out because I had some liquids that were really yearning to get out, if you know what I mean. I went in the hotel, did what I needed to, and ran right into(not literally) my parents as I was coming out. (They had gone up to check out the room.) We hopped back in the car and went to my great aunt\'s (my dad\'s aunt\'s) house. On the way, my dad was showing us all these places he had grwon up and everything it was really cool. He showed us his elementary school, his old house, where his middle school used to be where him and Mugsy, his dog, had walked through the snow when it snowed 18 inches, and other stuff like that haha. It was really cool. We got to Angie Hauser\'s house (my great aunt) and we started talkign to her and everything. MAn, I am tellin you, that is one hilarious old lady. She\'s 94 years and man, she is KICKIN. I mean she like goes all over the place and she doesn\'t even need a wheel chair or anything. My sister said somethign about what girls her age where and they started talking about TV and the media and everything. Before long this hilarious old lady started talking about boobs it was quite funny. She was like, \"Oh they know what boobs are!! They have heard that plenty on TV!\" hahaha Yeah it was hilarious. That is one funny old lady. Anyway, we hung around, I played guitar on the back porch, my dad showed his presentation for Mema (our grandma, my dad\'s mom), and all that stuff. More people came over, like our other relatives, I forgot to tell you that. We hung around there for awhile, then we went back to our hotel. We found out my uncle was rooming right next to us (he is our uncle on my mom\'s side that\'s why it was cool). He was down near Thomson for something the day before and he just stayed instead of having to drive all the way. He really likes his nephews and neices ( as in my brother and sister and I). He wanted us to do all this stuff with him it was cool. Jesse and I went in his room and watched part of some movie and thenwe went to bed. We woke up the next day around nine thirty or so and I was pretty tired, but I got up and took a shower an stuff. Then my mom brought me some breakfast from downstairs (because it was too early for me) because I had asked her to. We had to get into fancy clothes, (my mom would not stop yelling at use to do stuff. I can\'t stand going to hotels with her) and then we went down to the lobby. We talked to our relatives (everysingle person was here except for the 5 great grandchildren) for about an hour, then we headed to the funeral. I got to ride with my uncle (Tom) and he played some song for me that he had been singing all night. He said he was going to email me. I was like that\'s cool. We got to the funeral and everyone was scattered about. It was awkard. They asked me to carry to coffin. Not only me, but we all grabbed onto the handles and pulled it our of the van. It made em feel kind of weird. Everyone looking at us, even though there weren\'t all that many people. It was this big silver coffin. It was rectangular and rounded on the top. I wasn\'t really expecting anything, but if I had been, it wouldn\'t have been what I had expected it to look like. It looked sort of space aged and everything. They had the people go up that wanted to look in. I didn\'t look in it, but I stood next to it and just onlooked. It was awkward so I didn\'t want to go all the way up to see her. The guy to talk came up and everyone took a seat. I found a nice lil spot on the front row and sat down. The chairs look a lot comfier than they actually were. They were blue. The guy talked on and on about this stuff, he wasn\'t very good, but it was okay. My family didn\'t like it either, we had a discussion about it. After that, I jumped back into Tom\'s car and we headed over to my dad\'s church, where he grew up in, to have the memorial service. We went in, my dad set his presentation on his laptop up in the front of the church for people to watch and we went into the chapel and sat down. The same guy came up and talked. He did pretty much the exact same talk as he did earlier, but it was as boring because I coulld rest my head on the pew, and i got to sit with my sister. We got out of the service finally and I was STARVING but my mom could really care less. Luckily, my dad understood and he was like yeah, I am NOT going to wait until 5 (for the big dinner) to eat, so he gave us money to go to KFC. That was pretty aweosme. Also, Jimmy Hauser, Angie Hauser\'s son, gave us some brownies. That was cool, too. We sat around at the church for a couple hours until the dinner. My dad took us around and showed us all the stuff he used to do and where he would go for church and all that stuff. We went to dinner and I took a walk  around the church and listened to Holland so I ended up getting to dinner aftert they had already started. Listening to Holland reminded me of last Thanksgiving. It was sad sort of, but also very happy. I didn\'t want to go to Tulsa (in Oklahoma) for Thanksgiving, but it was the last time we were going to get to go there and one of the last things to do with my sister. It was a bittersweet week. I like it but it was sort of broing. I listened to music a lot and reflected. I did that in Thomson the last couple of days, too. I don\'t really know what to think about my grandma dying. I won\'t really miss her, since I wasn\'t around her that long, but looking at the pictures it made me sad. It made me want to do more stuff with her, because I never really got to do anything except for when I was little. We saw her all the time then. I came to dinner and didn\'t really have anywhere to sit. The table my family was at was full, so I sat with Stephen, Laurie, and my uncle Ernie\'s family. I wasn\'t that hungry because i had KFC, but i had a little bit of green beans and ham and a roll. After the dinner, we talked for a little and took pictures (it was the first time the entire family was together, except Mema) and eventually we left to go back to the hotel. We hung around for a little bit and changed and stuff and talked about the service, etc. I changed into jeans, put on my hat, and went across the street to buy some milk at the Racetrac. I came back and we all went down  to the lobby again. I brought the Lucky Charms and the milk and a bowl and sppon and sat down at one of the tables. I sat down and opened the Lucky Charms (it was brand new, unopened) and started eating. When I was done, there weren\'t any lucky charms left. I guess I was hungry. Later that night, we went to Dairy Queen with Linsey, Shelley, and my brother and I. I got an oreo blizzard. I got a dime in that little thing where you drop a cion in the water and get it in the cup, but it had to be a quarter. I saw condoms in the gas station it was connected to and it made me feel bad. It made me think about all the sin and stuf in the world and how people get addicted to drugs and they can\'t afford it finaccially so they go into stuff like prostitution and everything. I wondered how much they costed, but didn\'t want to draw attention to them. I just noticed them as I was walking by. We got back in the car and went back to the hotel. We went in the lobby because my parents were at Wal-Mart and they had the key. Lindsey, my brother, and I talked for a long time then we went to the front desk and got a key for our room. We went up there and about 2 minutes later, our parents showed up. It was kind of annoying cause we were in the lobby for about half an hour waiting for them. It was kind of funny though. Lindsey hung around for a little while in our room and we watched the Cosby Show and stuff. I LOVE that show. It\'s the only show on TV worth watching. It\'s hilarious. Lindsey left after awhile, and we all got inot bed. We talked for a long time about the bad stuff we had done and our dad told us stories about when he was small and stuff like that. Evetually, They ticked me off and I was like screw you and i put on my headphones. The next morning my brother was yellign at us to wake up and being a huge pain in the butt and decided that (ONLY because I started it!!!) he was going to start guitar. Luckily, I don\'t think he\'ll hold up to it, and if he does, he won\'t be able to play anything so it\'s okay. He plays drums anyway. We did that whole deal about my mom yellin at us for like an hour while we were packing and everything. We got packed, and went to Angie Hausers to eat. We hung around just like we had been doign the whole time and ate. We left and then went to the grave one last time to see her after they buried her. We talked about her will and what we were gonna do to our own bodies and how it should be up to your relatives since you\'re dead and it doesn\'t matter. Then we got in the car and headed home. I got in the front this time. We went to an Ingles so that my mom and sister could get some stuff for cookies. They made them a little while I think. I should go see if they\'re ready so that I can eat them. It\'s been an okay last couple of days, but it was very boring. It was sad, but we had a good time and I think that Mema would be happy about that. She doesn\'t want us to be sad aobut her leaving. She left on such a perfect day. Three days before he aniversery. Easter Sunday....','When two plus two doesn\'t come out to four.','','publish','open','open','','when-two-plus-two-doesnt-come-out-to-four','','','2004-04-16 10:32:00','2004-04-16 10:32:00','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/journal/?p=123',0,'post','',6),(124,2,'2004-04-16 14:46:00','2004-04-16 14:46:00','<img src=\"http://live.quizilla.com/user_images/1034277815_tioncuddle.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"cuddle and a kiss\"><br />cuddle and a kiss on the forehead - you like to be<br />close to your special someone and feel warm,<br />comfortable, and needed\r\n<br /><br /><a href=\"http://quizilla.com/users/theandrea/quizzes/What%20Sign%20of%20Affection%20Are%20You%3F/\"> <font size=\"-1\">What Sign of Affection Are You?</font></a><br /> <font size=\"-3\">brought to you by <a href=\"http://quizilla.com\">Quizilla</a></font>\r\n\r\n\r\nHmmm...interesting. Good thing I don\'t look like that.','Well...','','publish','open','open','','well','','','2004-04-16 14:46:00','2004-04-16 14:46:00','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/journal/?p=124',0,'post','',0),(125,2,'2004-04-17 01:05:00','2004-04-17 01:05:00','This is really stupid.','>:O','','publish','open','open','','o','','','2004-04-17 01:05:00','2004-04-17 01:05:00','',0,'http://jrstrauss.net/journal/?p=125',0,'post','',0),(126,2,'2004-04-17 01:19:00','2004-04-17 01:19:00','Emery is good for when you\'re mad.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARE YOU LISTENING?!\r\nWE WRITE A THOUSAND PAGES\r\nTHEY\'RE TORN AND ON THE FLOOR\r\nAND LIGHTS HAMMER THE WINDOWS\r\nWERE LOCKED BEHIND THESE DOORS\r\nAND WE ARE NEVER LEAVING\r\nTHIS PLACE IS PART OF US\r\n\r\n\r\