:44','',661,'http://journal.rruffles.com/661-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(667,2,'2012-09-17 21:47:09','2012-09-18 01:47:09','I thought my life was going to go one way and then it went another. I’m fine with it most days but then there are certain moments, such as these, when I’m suffocated by the weight of my own failures. I’ve pretended for so long that this part of me was shut off, damaged goods, that it just wasn’t ever going to happen for me. I became resigned and defeated. Content with my discontent.\n\nThen the fire will spark and I’ll feel cheated. All of a sudden, I want to get what’s owed to me. I want to get more than what I currently have.\n\nI’m talking here about love, of course. The act of getting it and then sustaining the connection. Growing up, I always knew that I had a lot of love to give. I felt everything; I felt everyone. I’m always placing my hand on a friend’s body out of habit just so I can be closer to them. There’s no such thing as too close. I’m always looking for connections wherever I go.\n\n<em>Remind me why I’m here. C’mere.</em>\n\nI imagined my young adult life to be spent in a series of different people’s beds, limbs entangled, light peeking through the window, fingertips going up and down the back to initiate morning sex. I can so clearly visualize the scene: I’m cooking breakfast for someone. Music is wafting through the laptop speakers and I’m watching a man get dressed. I’m watching his ass, the curve of his back, as he gets clothed and moves forward to kiss me goodbye. Then, when he leaves, the energy will get sucked from the room, the spell will be broken, and I’ll need to go get it again.\n\nSounds familiar, right? Sounds like something that’s plucked from the pages of your life? I know it is because I’ve been studying it. But despite all of my desire and wanting, there’s been no naked backs hanging from the edge of my bed, no quick passionate kisses goodbye while I’m still half-asleep. There’s been nothing.\n\nBecause of this, I don’t understand the motions of sex and love. I am not a part of the club.\n\nOf course, a lot of these failures have to do with me. You can only blame others for so long before realizing that you are a part of the problem. Perhaps what’s more adult than wearing your lover’s shirt and cooking breakfast for them in the morning is coming to the realization that you’re screwed up. Something inside of you broke and it’s up to you to fix it.\n\nHere’s another familiar scene for you: You look around a room that’s full of your friends and realize you are the only one who isn’t spoken for. Everyone else is clutching on to the arm of their partner while your grip on the bottle of wine stiffens.\n\nAnother one: You go on a family vacation and realize you are the only one who didn’t bring a significant other. You get to sleep on the pullout because it’s only you and it’s better for one person to be uncomfortable rather than two. <em>Actually, I guarantee that I’m the one who will be in more pain BECAUSE I’m alone.</em>\n\nLast one: A man brushes your shoulder on the subway and your body practically has convulsions. It’s then that you realize that you haven’t been touched in a long time.\n\nIt’s easy to sit here and ask, “When will I be spoken for? When will I have someone to bring on the family vacation? When will I get used to someone’s touch?”\n\nWhen will it be my turn to fall in love?\n\nI don’t know. No one knows. Stop buying the books that tell you when because they’re merely profiting off of your vulnerabilities. Just focus on yourself and pray that the fire never stops sparking. Pray that you never get used to all of this because the second you do, it’s yours forever.','when will it be my turn to fall in love?','','inherit','open','closed','','666-revision','','','2012-09-17 21:47:09','2012-09-18 01:47:09','',666,'http://journal.rruffles.com/666-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(668,2,'2012-09-22 04:01:49','2012-09-22 08:01:49','I\'ve never had anyone treat me like such shit. And the worst part is that you don\'t care and you never will.','','','private','open','closed','','668','','','2012-10-01 22:03:28','2012-10-02 02:03:28','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=668',0,'post','',0),(669,2,'2012-09-22 04:01:49','2012-09-22 08:01:49','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','closed','','668-revision','','','2012-09-22 04:01:49','2012-09-22 08:01:49','',668,'http://journal.rruffles.com/668-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(670,2,'2012-09-22 04:01:49','2012-09-22 08:01:49','I\'ve never had anyone treat me like such shit. And the worst part is that you don\'t care and you never will.','','','inherit','open','closed','','668-revision-2','','','2012-09-22 04:01:49','2012-09-22 08:01:49','',668,'http://journal.rruffles.com/668-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(671,2,'2012-09-24 14:09:07','2012-09-24 18:09:07','I have an absolutely debilitating fear of being alone. I\'m completely paralyzed in fear. And I\'m teetering over the edge about to fall to my death.','fear','','publish','open','closed','','fear','','','2012-10-01 22:02:29','2012-10-02 02:02:29','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=671',0,'post','',0),(672,2,'2012-09-24 14:08:18','2012-09-24 18:08:18','','fear','','inherit','open','closed','','671-revision','','','2012-09-24 14:08:18','2012-09-24 18:08:18','',671,'http://journal.rruffles.com/671-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(674,2,'2012-09-27 01:59:39','2012-09-27 05:59:39','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','closed','','673-revision','','','2012-09-27 01:59:39','2012-09-27 05:59:39','',673,'http://journal.rruffles.com/673-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(700,2,'2012-10-23 16:26:03','2012-10-23 20:26:03','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','closed','','699-revision','','','2012-10-23 16:26:03','2012-10-23 20:26:03','',699,'http://journal.rruffles.com/699-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(676,2,'2012-09-28 15:23:24','2012-09-28 19:23:24','The past is a ghost, the future a dream, and all we ever have is now.','now','','publish','open','closed','','now','','','2012-10-01 22:00:34','2012-10-02 02:00:34','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=676',0,'post','',0),(677,2,'2012-09-28 15:23:17','2012-09-28 19:23:17','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','closed','','676-revision','','','2012-09-28 15:23:17','2012-09-28 19:23:17','',676,'http://journal.rruffles.com/676-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(678,2,'2012-09-28 15:23:24','2012-09-28 19:23:24','The past is a ghost, the future a dream and all we ever have is now.','now','','inherit','open','closed','','676-revision-2','','','2012-09-28 15:23:24','2012-09-28 19:23:24','',676,'http://journal.rruffles.com/676-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(679,2,'2012-10-01 21:39:24','2012-10-02 01:39:24','The way you treat me is completely unfair. In fact, everything you do to me is unfair. You apply such an extreme double standard that I have never experienced with anyone I\'ve ever known. And the worst part is that you get away with it. I will always fight to be the better person. I will always offer the treatment that I wish I could receive from you. Though I am doubtful, I pray that it will one day pay off.\r\n\r\nWhen I was younger, I wished to be like my mother. She is a bottomless fountain of mercy. She is a bottomless fountain of wisdom. After growing up with her in the family, taking care and neutralizing every single emotional crisis and conflict, it was something I could not miss. I was amazed by her ability to put her own needs so far behind her and give them away to us. It was a bittersweet desire. I admired the ability, yet I did not want the responsibility of learning how to live without having my needs met, shoving everything to the back to make room for my family\'s well-being. Though I didn\'t worry about this bittersweet desire, for I didn\'t believe I was like that. I didn\'t believe it was an ability I possessed. I believed it was a talent my mother was blessed with--that I don\'t see in anyone else in my family--that I was not blessed with. I didn\'t believe that I had that ability, but deep down inside I wanted it when I grew older.\r\n\r\nYet, I am beginning to see it in myself. And it grows bigger and bigger everyday. Will I one day be like my mother, much more worried about the most precious relationships in my life, when their behavior is completely irrational, selfish, and unjustified? Am I falling into a life of unconditional and seemingly bottomless prioritization of other\'s over my own needs? Who will care for me? Who will look out for me? What about the times when those that I love and look to for support are those that tear my world apart? I am beginning to see this in my own life. My doubts reside in what this will mean for me--does it mean my efforts will be doubled back by love and support or that I\'m simply diving without safety nets?\r\n\r\nWell here\'s the start. You have lied to me. You have cheated me out of what I wanted for my own life. You used your own selfish confusions to take advantage of me, what I wanted, and what I had planned for. You made me challenge my own values in ways that were not healthy for me and in ways that perpetuated your own misguided search for which you don\'t even know what. You made me realize that I am nothing but a worthless human. You made me realize that I am less than I ever thought I was. You made me realize I am nothing but a fool.\r\n\r\nYou brought me down with you. And the worst part about it is that you didn\'t bring me down, you influenced me to come down with you. Even worse, it was a pure, raw decision--a decision that no one made except myself. You couldn\'t force me to do anything. I made the decision myself. And you made me want it. You made me want it with absolutely no repercussions to your own well-being. And that\'s what hurts the most. Because after everything is said and done, it means nothing to you. It means nothing to you what I go through. It means nothing to you where I came from. I had no idea I was diving into my own suicide. I thought I was diving into an era of safety, of support. Yet I took a leap of faith, put my trust in you, and felt my stomach pass through my head as I began to free-fall, looking to you in fear and finding you nowhere in sight.\r\n\r\nYou\'ve taught me that no one will ever provide the support that I need other than myself. You\'ve taught me that I will always fend for myself. You\'ve taught me that I am my own greatest resource on this Earth for anything I will ever need. You\'ve taught me that I must remain strong for myself, for if I do not, no one will.','essential independence','','publish','open','closed','','essential-independence','','','2012-11-29 10:38:36','2012-11-29 15:38:36','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=679',0,'post','',0),(680,2,'2012-10-01 21:38:06','2012-10-02 01:38:06','The way you treat me is completely unfair. In fact, everything you do to me is unfair. You apply such an extreme double standard that I have never experienced with anyone I\'ve ever known. And the worst part is that you get away with it. I will always fight to be the better person. I will always offer the treatment that I wish I could receive from you. Though I am doubtful, I pray that it will one day pay off.\n\nWhen I was younger, I wished to be like my mother. She is a bottomless fountain of mercy. She is a bottomless fountain of wisdom. After growing up with her in the family, taking care and neutralizing every single emotional crisis and conflict, it was something I could not miss. I was amazed by her ability to put her own needs so far behind her and give them away to us. It was a bittersweet desire. I admired the ability, yet I did not want the responsibility of learning how to live without having my needs met, shoving everything to the back to make room for my family\'s well-being. Though I didn\'t worry about this bittersweet desire, for I didn\'t believe I was like that. I didn\'t believe it was an ability I possessed. I believed it was a talent my mother was blessed wi