o you what I go through. It means nothing to you where I came from. I had no idea I was diving into my own suicide. I thought I was diving into an era of safety, of support. Yet I took a leap of faith, put my trust in you, and felt my stomach pass through my head as I began to free-fall, looking to you in fear and finding you no where in sight.\r\n\r\nYou\'ve taught me that no one will ever provide the support that I need other than myself. You\'ve taught me that I will always fend for myself. You\'ve taught me that I am my own greatest resource on this Earth for anything I will ever need. You\'ve taught me that I must remain strong for myself, for if I do not, no one will.','essential independence','','inherit','open','closed','','679-revision-2','','','2012-10-01 21:39:24','2012-10-02 01:39:24','',679,'http://journal.rruffles.com/679-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(683,2,'2012-11-29 10:36:28','2012-11-29 15:36:28','The way you treat me is completely unfair. In fact, everything you do to me is unfair. You apply such an extreme double standard that I have never experienced with anyone I\'ve ever known. And the worst part is that you get away with it. I will always fight to be the better person. I will always offer the treatment that I wish I could receive from you. Though I am doubtful, I pray that it will one day pay off.\n\nWhen I was younger, I wished to be like my mother. She is a bottomless fountain of mercy. She is a bottomless fountain of wisdom. After growing up with her in the family, taking care and neutralizing every single emotional crisis and conflict, it was something I could not miss. I was amazed by her ability to put her own needs so far behind her and give them away to us. It was a bittersweet desire. I admired the ability, yet I did not want the responsibility of learning how to live without having my needs met, shoving everything to the back to make room for my family\'s well-being. Though I didn\'t worry about this bittersweet desire, for I did