will always offer the treatment that I wish I could receive from you. Though I am doubtful, I pray that it will one day pay off.\r\n\r\nWhen I was younger, I wished to be like my mother. She is a bottomless fountain of mercy. She is a bottomless fountain of wisdom. After growing up with her in the family, taking care and neutralizing every single emotional crisis and conflict, it was something I could not miss. I was amazed by her ability to put her own needs so far behind her and give them away to us. It was a bittersweet desire. I admired the ability, yet I did not want the responsibility of learning how to live without having my needs met, shoving everything to the back to make room for my family\'s well-being. Though I didn\'t worry about this bittersweet desire, for I didn\'t believe I was like that. I didn\'t believe it was an ability I possessed. I believed it was a talent my mother was blessed with--that I don\'t see in anyone else in my family--that I was not blessed with. I didn\'t believe that I had that ability, but deep down inside I wanted it when I grew older.\r\n\r\nYet, I am beginning to see it in myself. And it grows bigger and bigger everyday. Will I one day be like my mother, much more worried about the most precious relationships in my life, when their behavior is completely irrational, selfish, and unjustified? Am I falling into a life of unconditional and seeming bottomless prioritization of others over my own needs? Who will care for me? Who will look out for me? What about the times when those that I love and look to for support are those that tear my world apart? I am beginning to see this in my own life. My doubts reside in what this will mean for me--does it mean my efforts will be doubled back by love and support or that I\'m simply diving without safety nets?\r\n\r\nWell here\'s the start. You have lied to me. You have cheated me out of what I wanted for my own life. You used your own selfish confusions to take advantage of me, what I wanted, and what I had planned for. You made me challenge my own values in ways that were not healthy for me and in ways that perpetuated your own misguided search for which you don\'t even know what. You made me realize that I am nothing but a worthless human. You made me realize that I am less than I ever thought I was. You made me realize I am nothing but a fool.\r\n\r\nYou brought me down with you. And the worst part about it is that you didn\'t bring me down, you influenced me to come down with you. Even worse, it was a pure, raw decision--a decision that no one made except myself. You couldn\'t force me to do anything. I made the decision myself. And you made me want it. You made me want it with absolutely no repercussions to your own well-being. And that\'s what hurts the most. Because after everything is said and done, it means nothing to you. It means nothing to you what I go through. It means nothing to you where I came from. I had no idea I was diving into my own suicide. I thought I was diving into an era of safety, of support. Yet I took a leap of faith, put my trust in you, and felt my stomach pass through my head as I began to free-fall, looking to you in fear and finding you no where in sight.\r\n\r\nYou\'ve taught me that no one will ever provide the support that I need other than myself. You\'ve taught me that I will always fend for myself. You\'ve taught me that I am my own greatest resource on this Earth for anything I will ever need. You\'ve taught me that I must remain strong for myself, for if I do not, no one will.','essential independence','','inherit','open','closed','','679-revision-3','','','2012-10-01 21:46:54','2012-10-02 01:46:54','',679,'http://journal.rruffles.com/679-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(720,2,'2012-11-29 10:29:28','2012-11-29 15:29:28','The way you treat me is completely unfair. In fact, everything you do to me is unfair. You apply such an extreme double standard that I have never experienced with anyone I\'ve ever known