ing a good time on your hike. I can\'t wait for you to get back home where you belong (I hope). You\'ll be back in the U.S./society in no time and wishing you were back in New Zealand, but don\'t fall into the trap of always wishing you were somewhere else. Hiking is great but so is the joy of gaining your own independence in other ways that are more sustainable. The Double IPA that I was telling you about when you left earlier was ready just in time for<strong> </strong>the<strong> </strong>Georgia homebrew competition (Peach State Brew Off) and we won Honorable Mention (just behind 3rd) in the Strong Ale category. We scored a 41/50 and the competition standards rate 45-50 as \"world-class beers.\" Of course I have a tall bottle waiting for you when you get here. Can\'t wait to see you soon, Russell.','','','publish','open','closed','','846','','','2016-03-09 01:44:41','2016-03-09 06:44:41','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=846',0,'post','',0),(834,2,'2015-05-19 19:52:46','2015-05-19 23:52:46','14. Devin Patrick\r\n5.19.2015\r\n\r\nDevin looks like a movie star. Very risky, but we wanted each other so bad. We said we could wait and then we couldn\'t. Tons of buildup. In the hammock only feet away from mom and sister\'s tent. I\'ve never experienced so much silence, this time when we needed noise the most. Quietest on the entire trail. Short and clumsy, but so, so good. Lied down in the softest grassy patch, Ash Gap on top of Roan Mountain underneath the silent stars.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://journal.rruffles.com/wp-content/uploads/devin.jpg\" alt=\"devin\" />','Devin Patrick','','private','open','closed','','834','','','2017-03-27 14:11:28','2017-03-27 18:11:28','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=834',0,'post','',0),(835,2,'2015-11-03 19:59:04','2015-11-04 00:59:04','Devin Patrick\r\n\r\n5.19.2015\r\n\r\nDevin looks like a movie star. Very risky, but we wanted each other so bad. We said we could wait and then we couldn\'t. Tons of buildup. In the hammock only feet away from mom and sister\'s tent. I\'ve never experienced so much silence, this time when we needed noise the most. Quietest on the entire trail. Short and clumsy, but so, so good. Lied down in the softest grassy patch, Ash Gap on top of Roan Mountain underneath the silent stars.','','','inherit','open','closed','','834-revision-v1','','','2015-11-03 19:59:04','2015-11-04 00:59:04','',834,'http://journal.rruffles.com/834-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(836,2,'2015-05-14 20:00:16','2015-05-15 00:00:16','13. Nicole Cyr\r\n5.14.15\r\n\r\nWorked out quite nicely. Fun and exciting. Beautiful spot by the river for a hiker festival called Trail Days. Followed by three more nights by the river and in the river. Amazing purple hair.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<img style=\"display: block; margin: 0 auto; max-width: 50%;\" src=\"http://journal.rruffles.com/wp-content/uploads/nicole.jpg\" />','Nicole Cyr','','private','open','closed','','836','','','2017-03-27 14:11:47','2017-03-27 18:11:47','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=836',0,'post','',0),(837,2,'2015-11-03 20:03:22','2015-11-04 01:03:22','Nicole Cyr\r\n\r\n5.14.15\r\n\r\nWorked out quite nicely. Fun and exciting. Beautiful spot by the river for a hiker festival called Trail Days. Followed by three more nights by the river and in the river. Amazing purple hair.','','','inherit','open','closed','','836-revision-v1','','','2015-11-03 20:03:22','2015-11-04 01:03:22','',836,'http://journal.rruffles.com/836-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(839,2,'2015-12-17 20:58:30','2015-12-18 01:58:30','The strangest thing happened to me a few days ago. I suppose it is not that strange. It\'s quite explicable if you think about it for more than a second, really. I needed a spot to relax for a bit, so I found a wonderfully quiet spot under a big tree in Freedom Park in the dark. I sparked up a joint and sat there for a few minutes. Before long, a group of four dark figures walked up, one carrying a flash light. They didn\'t look like the law, so I quickly put the joint away and sat there. They came up to me, man with flashlight in front, and he leaned down in front of me. He told me that he was with a charity and asked me if I want any food. I was taken by total surprise and didn\'t know how to react, so I just told him, \"No, I\'m okay.\"\r\n\r\n\"Any blankets or jackets?\"\r\n\r\nQuietly and politely, \"No, I just want some peace.\"\r\n\r\nThey left and made a big loop around the section of the park before leaving. I think they had just come there for me. I hadn\'t been under the tree for more than five or ten minutes. I had noticed a tall boy in a bag as I approached the large trunk of the tree. So it made sense. But it was startling. Not all that bothersome, but it took me by surprise.\r\n\r\nIt at least proved a point to me, in the case that I hadn\'t noticed it already. Since I have been traveling the world by foot, many more interesting things happen in your daily life. Sure, they\'re typically only mildly interesting, but they\'re things that don\'t happen to you in your car; don\'t happen to you in your house; don\'t happen to you if you\'re not out walking around. Since I don\'t have a designated place that I can relax, I\'ve been wandering about. I\'ve been riding the bus. I\'ve been taking my time getting from place to place.\r\n\r\nYou get to hear other people\'s stories. Even if you\'re not looking for them. I\'m terrible at striking it up with other people. But sometimes being somewhere unexpected is the common ground, or if nothing else, at least the instigation.','a mobile routine','','publish','open','closed','','839','','','2015-12-20 13:49:38','2015-12-20 18:49:38','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=839',0,'post','',0),(840,2,'2015-12-17 20:58:30','2015-12-18 01:58:30','The strangest thing happened to me a few days ago. I suppose it is not that strange. It\'s quite explicable if you think about it for more than a second, really. I needed a spot to relax for a bit, so I found a wonderfully quiet spot under a big tree in Freedom Park in the dark. I sparked up a joint and sat there for a few minutes. Before long, a group of four dark figures walked up, one carrying a flash light. They didn\'t look like the law, so I quickly put the joint away and sat there. They came up to me, man with flashlight in front, and he leaned down in front of me. He told me that he was with a charity and asked me if I want any food. I was taken by total surprise and didn\'t know how to react, so I just told him, \"No, I\'m okay.\"\r\n\r\n\"Any blankets or jackets?\"\r\n\r\nQuietly and politely, \"No, I just want some peace.\"\r\n\r\nThey left and made a big loop around the section of the park before leaving. I think they had just come there for me. I hadn\'t been under the tree for more than five or ten minutes. I had noticed a tall boy in a bag as I approached the large trunk of the tree. So it made sense. But it was startling. Not all that bothersome, but it took me by surprise.\r\n\r\nIt at least proved a point to me, in the case that I hadn\'t noticed it already. Since I have been traveling the world by foot, many more interesting things happen in your daily life. Sure, they\'re typically only mildly interesting, but they\'re things that don\'t happen to you in your car; don\'t happen to you in your house; don\'t happen to you if you\'re not out walking around. Since I don\'t have a designated place that I can relax, I\'ve been wandering about. I\'ve been riding the bus. I\'ve been taking my time getting from place to place.\r\n\r\nYou get to hear other people\'s stories. Even if you\'re not looking for them. I\'m terrible at striking it up with other people. But sometimes being somewhere unexpected is the common ground, or if nothing else, at least the instigation.','','','inherit','open','closed','','839-revision-v1','','','2015-12-17 20:58:30','2015-12-18 01:58:30','',839,'http://journal.rruffles.com/839-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(842,2,'2015-12-19 10:50:48','2015-12-19 15:50:48','I want to describe a time in my life that I will never forget. I should have done it long ago, while it was still fresh in my memory, but the longer I wait, the foggier it will get. Only months later, and it\'s already starting to fade. It\'s so sad, because they\'re some of the most precious memories I\'ve ever made in my entire life. I\'m so passionately dreading the day when I can\'t remember every little single detail of those three weeks of my life--and that is already starting to happen. I would give anything to have every moment perfectly documented out and preserved forever. So I must remember everything I can possibly remember before it fades away.\n\nOn one Saturday night, 3 weeks before my college graduation--the last semester of my senior year of college, I went to a party at my good friend Lee\'s. It was April 14th, 2012. He had these parties often--probably once a month, and my best friend David and I had been frequenting them quite often that semester in particular. They weren\'t always packed, and they weren\'t always crazy, but sometimes they were, and they were most usually always fun. I got to see the circle of friends that would always be there, so I enjoyed going to see them and have a good time. This one in particular was one of the last. There weren\'t that many people there because they had just had one recently, but in the end, it was a solid group of people and everyone ended up having a wonderful time. There had been a girl I had somewhat expressed interest in, and I wanted to take her and show her how much fun my group of friends had when they party, yet I never expected I would meet someone that would completely change my life.\n\nI knew most everyone there. I met a couple new faces, and then had gotten acquainted with basically everyone at the party. I had a pretty big reputation among this group of friends, so it typically wasn\'t difficult to make friends with everyone there. Although, there were two girls whom I didn\'t recognize after I knew everyone, so I just decided to introduce myself.\n\n-\"Hey, I\'m Megan.\"\n-\"And I\'m Clara.\"\n-\"Clara?\"\n-\"Yeah.\"\n-\"Cool, hey.\"\n\nThey\'re both very attractive young ladies, and they seemed to be having a very good time, but Clara was absolutely stunning. The longer I looked at her, the more beautiful I realized she was. I didn\'t talk to them really, but continued to mingle and have fun. Later in the night, Clara was nearby as I was talking to someone, and she grabbed my glasses and my hat off of me. It was my favorite hat of all time--the Cleveland Indians hat from my little league baseball team that I had from when I was a litte kid. I was desperately terrified of losing it whenever I took it out of the house. I thought about trying to grab it back, I might have even tried, but thought to myself, \"Well, I guess I\'m not getting that back right away. I\'ll get it back later.\" I thoroughly enjoyed the attention from her, so I was relaxed about it. I knew it would give me an excuse to talk to her later.\n\nTime passed, and I eventually went to the dance floor where I saw her, along with Megan and their friend William, dancing. Megan and William were dancing together. Clara had on the cutest red dress on, and I just couldn\'t get over how adorable she was. She was still wearing my hat and glasses. It was funny because she had probably had them on for at least 20 minutes, but I think it was even longer than that. I grabbed them back. She grabbed me and started dancing with me. I will never forget that moment because literally all I could think was, \"Is this really happening to me?\" That never happened with me. I never got to dance with girls, much less get grabbed by them. We held hands and danced for a long time. Neither of us were very drunk; I was sober enough for it to be self-conscious and awkward feeling, but I was still having a good time. I didn\'t ever want it to end. I felt weird about it because I had brought a different girl to the party to try and impress her, but in this moment, I really didn\'t care. I didn\'t expect it to go anywhere, but I was holding her hands and dancing with her--I never wanted it to end. Before a long time at all, Megan and William decided that it was time to leave. She told me she had to go. I was disappointed that she was leaving so soon, but there was nothing I could really do about it.\n\n\"Hey! This was fun! Will you find me on Facebook?\" She gave me the strangest look of disdain. I didn\'t understand it. But without hesitating for even half a second, I corrected myself: \"No! No! I\'ll find YOU! What\'s your last name?\"\n\n\"Gilbert.\"\n\nAnd then she left. I didn\'t really know what to do at this point. I continued to mingle with my friends and have fun, but was sad it had ended so soon. I didn\'t know if I would ever even see her again. I might have stayed another hour or two, then I went home. Berenice wasn\'t feeling good, but when she felt good enough to go, her, David, and I left to walk home. We got home and I tucked Berenice in and went to sleep in my own bed. All I could think about was Clara. I stayed up so long thinking about her that night. I had even friended her on Facebook before I got in bed. While lying in bed, I decided I would ask for her number the next day, call her up, and immediately ask her out for dinner for the following weekend. It was a Saturday night. I would typically never have the confidence to do something so suddenly, but I guess that\'s just the kind of thing love at first sight does to you. I also didn\'t have much time before summer came and everyone left. I had no idea if she would be here for the summer.\n\nI woke up the next morning and sent her a message:\n<div>-\"CLARA!\"</div>\n<div>-\"RUSSELL!\"</div>\n<div>-\"so i guess we are friends now...\"</div>\n<div>-\"Of course we are! it was destiny.</div>\n<div>clara, I had so much fun dancing with you last night. I want to hang out more.\"</div>\n<div>-\"ok. done. i love adventures.\"</div>\n<div>-\"HAHA.</div>\n<div>perfect.</div>\n<div>what\'s your phone number?\"</div>\n<div>-\"478 251 1493</div>\n<div>you are only slightly creepy by the way, but thats ok, because I think you are fun.\"</div>\n<div>-\"haha what! why am I creepy??\"</div>\n<div>-\"finding me and asking for my number...</div>\n<div>its ok.\"</div>\n<div>-\"you don\'t make friends with people after you meet them?\"</div>\n<div>-\"you are probably looking at all my friends and pictures as we speak</div>\n<div>.... hahaha\"\n<div>-\"what kind of adventure do you want to go on?\"</div>\n<div>-\"well i have a feeling you are a pretty adventurous kid, so i am willing to let you make that call.\"Her calling me \"creepy\" robbed me of all the confidence I needed to call her up and ask her out right then and there. I sent her my number and a text or two, but was very conservative about it. Yet, the texts just continued back and forth; I didn\'t want to push it too hard. David and I were out shooting for our documentary, and Clara was in studio while we texted back in forth. Later, I got a text that made me terrified.\n\n-\"I need a break.\"\nI hesitated then responded:\n-\"From me sending you silly pictures?\"\n-\"From studio.\"\nMy heart leapt, but I was still hesitant. I had only met her the night before. It was around 3 o\'clock.\n-\"Did you want to meet up or do something?\"\n-\"Sure, I\'m going to church with a friend in about 2 hours, but I have a little time to kill before then.\"\n\nGood news. She\'s a Christian. That\'s cool. I got excited. I called her to ask what we wanted to do. I told her we didn\'t have much time, but I could come pick her up and we could go cruising around for a little bit. After taking care of the camera equipment and taking my project team back to their cars, I left to go meet up with her. She sat in the grass outside of the architecture building waiting. I didn\'t really know what we could do, but I wasn\'t extremely concerned or nervous. But I was nervous. We started driving and I suggested I could take her to a cool antique store in the Highlands that David and I had found. We went and browsed for a little bit, but it was already time for her to go for church. She was meeting a friend, and we were already a little late. She invited me, and we decided to meet her friend, Michael Chaney, there. It was such a good sign to me. We went, and I felt good vibes from her. Honestly, there wasn\'t really a time that I didn\'t get good vibes from her from the second I met her, with the exception of her calling me creepy. After getting out, Michael suggested exactly what I was hoping, \"Are you guys hungry?\" Clara was. They wanted to go to the new dining hall, which I had never gotten to go to since I hadn\'t had a meal plan since I had been a freshman and wanted to try out before I graduated. It was the perfect opportunity! As the night went on, we all ate dinner together and sat talking for a long time. We finally walked out the door and sat outside, talking and enjoying the night. It wasn\'t until ten o\'clock that we decided to go. Michael went back into his apartment at North Ave, and Clara and I walked down Techwood together, in the direction of both my car and her dorm. She had left her bag in my car. She got her bag and we stood there for a couple minutes. I asked her what she was going to do that night. She told me that she had to do laundry, but she hated doing it alone and all of her friends were busy (we had seen them as we walked down Techwood). I wanted to tell her I would come so badly, but I didn\'t want to push it too hard. I had only met her last night. And even though I thought she wanted me to, I wanted to play my cards right. We just sat there in silence and looked at each other. She smiled at me with the most charming smile that could drive a guy wild. And it drove me wild. I smiled back. We looked at each other without saying anything. It should have been awkward, but it wasn\'t. I felt so natural with her. I said goodbye and left. I was so ecstatic about how glorious the day had been. I met up with her a little bit before 5 o\'clock to possibly hang out for an hour and we had spent the entire evening together. I couldn\'t stop smiling.\n\nShe told me later that that moment was her favorite memory of us together: when we just looked at other smiling, not knowing what to do or say. She wanted to ask if I had any homework to do, if I wanted to come up to her room and study together. I would have said yes, but I suppose she was feeling the same way I was. I went home so happy and excited that night. I remember it vividly. I was already crazy about her.\n\nAnd after that, everything blurs together. It was a glorious three weeks, packed with time spent with her, school, graduation, finals, so much going on. I was living absolutely full speed. I\'m beginning to forget it all, but I would do anything to keep that from happening. It\'s all in my head, but I don\'t know how to extract it.\n\nThe next day, I felt much better. I just couldn\'t believe how well things had gone that day. We continued talking, continued texting. We found excuses to hang out. She told me about her \"double lofted megabed\" and her room. I was curious. She asked me to come study with her. We decided to pick up some beer, and I came over. We spent the evening doing homework together. I had gone over later in the evening, maybe 7 o\'clock. She talked the night before about how she didn\'t like sleeping alone, that her room was great for slumber parties. We relaxed, enjoyed each other\'s company, and got to know each other. It was a lucky night for me in that I didn\'t have that much work to do. I drank a lot more than she did. It got dark. It was dim in her room. As we sat in her room alone, she wrote me a message on a sticky note and stuck it to me. She wanted to kiss me. We went back and forth a few times. Then I kissed her. We spent time enjoying the moment, enjoying each other, learning the taste of each other. We thought about how we had met 2 nights earlier. We were lying down, and she got tired. She wanted to go to sleep. We laid in her bed until she fell asleep. I gave myself time to lie there and sober up, then I quietly got out of bed, slipped out the door, and drove home. That was the last night I ever slept alone until I graduated, she left for the summer, and we were forced apart.\n\n</div>\n<div>We did the same thing the next night, but this time I stayed. There wasn\'t really any question that I was going to. It was natural. From that day forward, we spent every second outside of class together. We ate lunch together, we ate dinner together, we spent time together every night, I went to visit her in studio, and I stayed with her every night.</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;','For my love, wherever I may find her','','inherit','open','closed','','589-autosave-v1','','','2015-12-19 10:50:48','2015-12-19 15:50:48','',589,'http://journal.rruffles.com/589-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(843,2,'2015-12-20 13:42:18','2015-12-20 18:42:18','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">stay focused</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">be who you are</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">trust in a wise friend</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">live off the land</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">glide through dark times</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">be observant</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">treasure the quiet times</p>','advice from an owl','','publish','open','closed','','advice-from-an-owl','','','2015-12-20 13:42:18','2015-12-20 18:42:18','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=843',0,'post','',0),(844,2,'2015-12-20 13:42:18','2015-12-20 18:42:18','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">stay focused</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">be who you are</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">trust in a wise friend</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">live off the land</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">glide through dark times</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">be observant</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">treasure the quiet times</p>','advice from an owl','','inherit','open','closed','','843-revision-v1','','','2015-12-20 13:42:18','2015-12-20 18:42:18','',843,'http://journal.rruffles.com/843-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(845,2,'2015-12-20 13:48:09','2015-12-20 18:48:09','The strangest thing happened to me a few days ago. I suppose it is not that strange. It\'s quite explicable if you think about it for more than a second, really. I needed a spot to relax for a bit, so I found a wonderfully quiet spot under a big tree in Freedom Park in the dark. I sparked up a joint and sat there for a few minutes. Before long, a group of four dark figures walked up, one carrying a flash light. They didn\'t look like the law, so I quickly put the joint away and sat there. They came up to me, man with flashlight in front, and he leaned down in front of me. He told me that he was with a charity and asked me if I want any food. I was taken by total surprise and didn\'t know how to react, so I just told him, \"No, I\'m okay.\"\r\n\r\n\"Any blankets or jackets?\"\r\n\r\nQuietly and politely, \"No, I just want some peace.\"\r\n\r\nThey left and made a big loop around the section of the park before leaving. I think they had just come there for me. I hadn\'t been under the tree for more than five or ten minutes. I had noticed a tall boy in a bag as I approached the large trunk of the tree. So it made sense. But it was startling. Not all that bothersome, but it took me by surprise.\r\n\r\nIt at least proved a point to me, in the case that I hadn\'t noticed it already. Since I have been traveling the world by foot, many more interesting things happen in your daily life. Sure, they\'re typically only mildly interesting, but they\'re things that don\'t happen to you in your car; don\'t happen to you in your house; don\'t happen to you if you\'re not out walking around. Since I don\'t have a designated place that I can relax, I\'ve been wandering about. I\'ve been riding the bus. I\'ve been taking my time getting from place to place.\r\n\r\nYou get to hear other people\'s stories. Even if you\'re not looking for them. I\'m terrible at striking it up with other people. But sometimes being somewhere unexpected is the common ground, or if nothing else, at least the instigation.','a mobile routine','','inherit','open','closed','','839-revision-v1','','','2015-12-20 13:48:09','2015-12-20 18:48:09','',839,'http://journal.rruffles.com/839-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(847,2,'2016-03-09 01:44:41','2016-03-09 06:44:41','https://open.spotify.com/track/5I6y1KWmUoV5YCaIEcs1qs\n\nI\'ll never forget the first time I heard this. It was one of the nights we just got drunk and hung and stayed up too late. I was about to quit my job for good and leave. I knew what I was doing, and I was glad to have someone I trusted around. I\'m glad you\'re having a good time on your hike. I can\'t wait for you to get back home where you belong (I hope). You\'ll be back in the U.S./society in no time and wishing you were back in New Zealand, but don\'t fall into the trap of always wishing you were somewhere else. Hiking is great but so is the joy of gaining your own independence in other ways that are more sustainable. The Double IPA that I was telling you about when you left earlier was ready just in time for<strong> </strong>the<strong> </strong>Georgia homebrew competition (Peach State Brew Off) and we won Honorable Mention (just behind 3rd) in the Strong Ale category. We scored a 41/50 and the competition standards rate 45-50 as \"world-class beers.\" Of course I have a tall bottle waiting for you when you get here. Can\'t wait to see you soon, Russell.','','','inherit','open','closed','','846-revision-v1','','','2016-03-09 01:44:41','2016-03-09 06:44:41','',846,'http://journal.rruffles.com/846-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(849,2,'2016-04-11 15:00:51','2016-04-11 19:00:51','\"<em>Brewing beer is my favorite thing in the entire world. Well, except for maybe having sex and smoking weed. But brewing beer is definitely my third favorite thing in the world.</em>\"\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">-Cuyler Repine</p>','brewer\'s mantra','','publish','open','closed','','brewers-mantra','','','2016-04-11 15:00:51','2016-04-11 19:00:51','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=849',0,'post','',0),(850,2,'2016-04-11 15:00:51','2016-04-11 19:00:51','\"<em>Brewing beer is my favorite thing in the entire world. Well, except for maybe having sex and smoking weed. But brewing beer is definitely my third favorite thing in the world.</em>\"\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">-Cuyler Repine</p>','brewer\'s mantra','','inherit','open','closed','','849-revision-v1','','','2016-04-11 15:00:51','2016-04-11 19:00:51','',849,'http://journal.rruffles.com/849-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(965,2,'2017-04-04 01:13:55','2017-04-04 05:13:55','If I ever have another trail name, I want to be night owl.','trail name','','publish','open','closed','','trail-name','','','2017-04-04 01:13:55','2017-04-04 05:13:55','',0,'http://journal.rruffles.com/?p=965',0,'post','',0),(853,2,'2016-11-27 19:54:17','2016-11-28 00:54:17','<em>Sometimes I get introduced to people and I say, \"Oh, nice to meet you,\" and they say, \"Uhhh, we\'ve met before.\" That\'s when you decide to never speak to that person again, if you can help it. Think about it: If they were that good at small talk, you would have remembered them. You only drink sidewalk slammers once a year these days, after all, so that shit isn\'t on you. At this point, the unmemorable person will start yammering on about some boring-as-fuck PR job. Slowly back away while suggesting that they become interesting in the future. </em>','Engaging in Small Talk','','publish','open','closed','','engaging-in-small-talk','','','2016-11-27 19:54:17','2016-11-28 00:54:17','',0,'htt