,'http://journal.rruffles.com/965-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(967,2,'2017-04-20 16:16:48','2017-04-20 20:16:48','The process of hiring &amp; employing is a two way street. If a company wants to hire you at $100,000, definitely they are planning to profit more than 100K themselves, probably much more. Otherwise they won\'t hire you. Companies are not in business for some other worldly altruistic cause, they want to make lots of profit out of your labor. So, they very much want to hire you. In fact they are desperate. E.g. Facebook &amp; Google competition.\n\nThe paradox is, even when the company\'s want/need for you is desperately crazy, they try to hide it in the \'people market\'. In fact they behave as if they really don\'t need you, as if they are doing you some extra-ordinary favor by employing you. In fact what they are actually doing in this \'trade negotiation\', is try to downgrade your value, at the beginning of negotiations. They imply that you that you need them more than they need you. All their tactics of recruiting are geared toward this.\n\nTo counter this, first, you need to aware of it &amp; second, join together with other top people in an online group, where you discuss employers. Discuss the whole process of recruiting &amp; whether it is fair &amp; equal.\n\nStart from discussion of the advertisement itself. E.g if they want to know your salary right at the start, should they not in their ad, give at least give a reasonably narrow salary range budgeted for that position. That would be equal &amp; fair. In some countries they actually is the standard practice.\n\nPractices we take for grated as \'unchangeable\' do get changed. E.g. in SV, the VC community has recently realized this (the two way traffic) when the entrepreneurs decided that not taking investor money is actually better in for them.\n\nIf the recruiters are \'partnering\' with the company, is it not their professional duty to inform their client company about this two way street &amp; refuse to deal with companies who insist on being unprofessional?','','','inherit','closed','closed','','756-autosave-v1','','','2017-04-20 16:16:48','2017-04-20 20:16:48','',756,'http://journal.rruffles.com/756-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(968,2,'2017-04-20 16:17:59','2017-04-20 20:17:59','The process of hiring &amp; employing is a two way street. If a company wants to hire you at $100,000, definitely they are planning to profit more than 100K themselves, probably much more. Otherwise they won\'t hire you. Companies are not in business for some other worldly altruistic cause, they want to make lots of profit out of your labor. So, they very much want to hire you. In fact they are desperate. E.g. Facebook &amp; Google competition.\r\n\r\nThe paradox is, even when the company\'s want/need for you is desperately crazy, they try to hide it in the \'people market\'. In fact they behave as if they really don\'t need you, as if they are doing you some extra-ordinary favor by employing you. In fact what they are actually doing in this \'trade negotiation\', is try to downgrade your value, at the beginning of negotiations. They imply that you that you need them more than they need you. All their tactics of recruiting are geared toward this.\r\n\r\nTo counter this, first, you need to aware of it &amp; second, join together with other top people in an online group, where you discuss employers. Discuss the whole process of recruiting &amp; whether it is fair &amp; equal.\r\n\r\nStart from discussion of the advertisement itself. E.g if they want to know your salary right at the start, should they not include it in their ad, then give at least give a reasonably narrow salary range budgeted for that position. That would be equal &amp; fair. In some countries that actually is the standard practice.\r\n\r\nPractices we take for granted as \'unchangeable\' do get changed. E.g. in SV, the VC community has recently realized this (the two way traffic) when the entrepreneu