 had the initial brainstorm for Velcro during a 1941 hunting trip, when he noticed how difficult it was to pick Alpine burrs off of his clothes.<br /><br />This means that tweets about Lady Gaga&rsquo;s lingerie can help someone debugging Perl code. (Or a tweet about Perl code may help Lady Gaga&rsquo;s underwear stylist.) A random scrap of information can trigger just the right conceptual collision. It&rsquo;s hard to know which scrap might do the trick, but that&rsquo;s the beauty of social networks &mdash; they constantly produce potential sparks, for free.<br /><br />The participatory nature of Twitter and Facebook also makes them excellent tools for supercharging creativity. Users finely craft their bons mots to grab people&rsquo;s attention and perhaps earn a retweet or two.<br /><br />As football coaches have long preached, you should practice like you play. Twitter and Facebook give knowledge workers the chance to turn downtime into a game where creativity and insight are rewarded, if only with digital pats on the back. Formulating a clever tweet about the latest Clipse record may not have much to do with an engineer&rsquo;s current project, but it demands far more inspired energy than reading the sports page. And didn&rsquo;t someone awfully smart once note that excellence, whether intellectual or physical, was a habit?<br /><br />Ah, right &mdash; it was @THE_REAL_SHAQ. Hmm, wonder what he&rsquo;s tweeting right now? Let me check.<br /><div style=\"text-align: right;\">-<em>Wired Magazine</em></div>','creative efficiency','','inherit','closed','closed','','501-revision-v1','','','2017-04-26 15:06:32','2017-04-26 19:06:32','',501,'http://journal.rruffles.com/501-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1024,2,'2017-04-26 15:07:34','2017-04-26 19:07:34','','the_fake_stars_above_us_by_seffis','','inherit','open','closed','','the_fake_stars_above_us_by_seffis','','','2017-04-26 15:07:34','2017-04-26 19:07:34','',496,'http://journal.rruffles.com/wp-content/uploads/the